{"id":"project-LICHEN-i6hd","title":"udp_checksum computes incorrectly when UDP header has odd length","description":"File: rust/lichen-ipv6/src/lib.rs:666-677

The UDP checksum function handles skipping the checksum field (bytes 6-7):

```rust
for i in (0..udp_header.len()).step_by(2) {
    if i == 6 {
        continue; // Skip checksum
    }
    let high = udp_header[i] as u32;
    let low = if i + 1 < udp_header.len() {
        udp_header[i + 1] as u32
    } else {
        0
    };
    sum += (high << 8) | low;
}
```

While UDP header is always 8 bytes, the defensive coding for odd length has a subtle issue:
- When i=6 (checksum field), it continues without processing
- But the loop still processes i=0,2,4,6,8... where i=8 is out of bounds for an 8-byte header

Actually, step_by(2) with 0..8 gives: 0, 2, 4, 6. So i=6 is the last iteration.
This is fine for standard UDP, but if udp_header were ever 7 bytes (corrupted), the loop would process bytes 0-1, 2-3, 4-5 but not handle byte 6 as an odd byte.

This is a minor edge case, but the function is inconsistent with how icmpv6_checksum handles odd bytes (which uses a separate check after the loop).

Recommend: Add similar odd-byte handling after the loop for consistency, or add assert!(udp_header.len() == 8) to document the assumption.","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:34:16.050606Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:34:16.050639Z"}
